	<div id="comment_top_65032065" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65032065" name="comment_link_65032065" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23558283&amp;cid=65032065" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65032065)" >Heavy suppressors, incorrectly installed cause iss</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65032065" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65032065); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>, Informative)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span>Anonymous Coward</span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65032065"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65032065">The (repeated) failure to feed is likely due to attaching a home-made suppressor. For most handguns you either need an extremely ultralightweight suppressor to allow rearward barrel travel after the shot or a special spring-assembly (called a 'booster') fitted between the barrel and suppressor.
<p>
Putting the same barrel/suppressor on a store-bought glock would have had the same issue, needing to manually cycle. Almost certainly had nothing to do with how the plastic lower reciever was made.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65032065">

</div>
